<Base title="PSALM — Pāṇinian Structured pretraining for Small LAnguage Models">
  <section>
    <h2>The short version</h2>
    <p>
      Most language models learn by reading a large fraction of the internet.
      PSALM asks a different question: can <em>structure</em> stand in for
      <em>scale</em>? We use Pāṇini's grammar of Sanskrit — arguably the most
      precise description of any human language ever written — as an engine that
      manufactures unlimited, perfectly-formed example sentences, and we use those
      to teach a small model the shape of language before it ever reads ordinary
      text. We then add a layer of classical Indian logic (Navya-Nyāya) to make
      its reasoning more disciplined.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>For researchers</h2>
    <p>
      PSALM trains one small multilingual decoder and reads it three ways. A
      Pāṇinian synthetic-Sanskrit pre-pretraining stage supplies a structural
      prior with gold kāraka annotations; real Sanskrit and BabyLM English supply
      competence and a peer-benchmarkable target. We test whether the Pāṇinian
      prior beats a matched k-Shuffle Dyck control on compositional generalization
      at a fixed token budget (H1), whether a six-phase Navya-Nyāya scaffold is
      more sample-efficient to install on a grammar-structured base than on a
      matched generic base (H2), and whether an epistemic constraint kernel
      enforces validity by construction (H3). Every claim is reported with
      bootstrap confidence intervals, permutation tests, and Holm–Bonferroni
      correction against pre-registered thresholds.
    </p>
    <p>
      We are explicit about scope. Grammar generates form, not facts; PSALM does
      not chase frontier parity, and world-knowledge benchmarks appear only as
      honest reference points. The full method, results, and limitations live in
      the <a href="https://github.com/SharathSPhD/PSALM">paper and repository</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Results</h2>
    <p>
      Results, figures, and tables are published here as each phase closes. This
      site is generated from the same findings that feed the paper, so the numbers
      shown are always the verified, signed-off ones — never projections.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Try it</h2>
    <p>
      Run-from-GitHub Colab notebooks and Hugging Face Space demos will be linked
      here so anyone can reproduce a result or talk to a model directly.
    </p>
  </section>
</Base>
